    "body": "Hi, I'm starting to use neovim (Linux). Linux programs generally provide a dedicated arg (e.g. -c, --config, -f, ...) to specify a user init file to be used instead of the program's default user init file. $VIMINIT supports general Ex commands. So the use of a command (e.g. \"source ...\") in $VIMINIT to specify an alternate user init file, may cause one to question whether such a use of $VIMINIT is a workaround/hook to leverage $VIMINIT to specify an alternate user init file, as opposed to an intended use of $VIMINIT. This is particularly so, because it's an atypical means (compared to other Linux programs) to specify an alternate user init file. At the same time, I do see the value in combining any general Ex commands with a command to specify an alternate user init file, because all init commands are in one place, which is good for organizing startup config. (It also allows experimentation with various init options without changing the init file, which seems handy.) So my suggestion is to confirm/clarify in the documentation that $VIMINIT is indeed the intended means to specify an alternate default user init file. (I also understand that -u is available, but -u appears to be a special use case, beyond simply specifying an alternate init file for user-specific preferences.)",
